Cook the farro: Wash and dry all produce. Place the @farro{1/2%cup} in a #medium pot{} with @water{2%cups} and @salt{large pinch}. Bring to a boil, reduce to a simmer, and cook for ~{20-25%minutes} until tender. Drain and return to the #pot.

While the farro cooks, cube the @Roma Tomato{2}. Halve, peel, and mince @Shallot{1}(peeled and minced). Cut the @Fresh Mozzarella{3%ounce} into small cubes. Thinly slice the @Basil{1/2%ounce} leaves into ribbons.

> TIP: You can add the basil stalks to the farro while it cooks. Just be sure to discard before serving.

Place your hand on top of the @Chicken Breasts{12%ounce} and slice into the middle of the meat, parallel to the #cutting board{}. Stop before cutting all the way through. Open the chicken up like a book. Repeat with the other chicken breast. Season on all sides with the @Herbes de Provence{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @Pepper{}.

In a #small bowl{}, stir together the shallot, @Balsamic Vinegar{2%tablespoon}, @Honey{1%ounce}, and a large drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%tablespoon} (to taste). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add the chicken to the pan and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} per side until golden brown and cooked through. Remove from the pan and set aside to rest.

Toss the salad: Toss the tomatoes, mozzarella, basil, and half the vinaigrette into the farro. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Thinly slice the herby pan-seared chicken and serve on a bed of caprese farro salad. Drizzle the remaining vinaigrette over top and enjoy!